  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (7941935 2022-07-11T00:09:05.617669537Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\n`forge init`\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nI ran `forge init` in a Git repo with some other changes in the git repo:\r\n\r\n![Screenshot from 2022-07-13 11-50-43](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12721972/178800781-e9e0d670-92ac-4989-859f-0e08516a6600.png)\r\n\r\nIt fails, because it says \"you have changes in your worktree\", but suggests that I run `forge init --no-commit` as a substitute.\r\n\r\nBut the second run of `forge init --no-commit` fails too, because the first run of `forge init` dumped a bunch of files in the current directory.\r\n\r\nThe first run of `forge init` should check _first_ if there will be git problems, then _not_ dump a bunch of files if there will be those problems, so that the second run with the suggested argument `--no-commit` will work.",
